article.description: Ron Mercer scored 19 points and Croshere had 11 of his season-high 17 in the decisive second quarter as the Pacers rolled to a 94-72 victory over the Denver Nuggets.
article.headline: Croshere scores season-high 17 for Indiana
article.linkText: Croshere seizes opportunity to help Pacers beat Nuggets
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- When inconsistent play and a sour attitude left Austin Croshere buried on the bench last season, he wondered if he'd ever get his minutes back.
Croshere

Coach Isiah Thomas told him he'd have to earn his minutes, and Croshere has gotten the message. Croshere scored a season-high 17 and Ron Mercer scored 19 points as the Indiana Pacers avenged their most embarrassing loss of the season with a 94-72 win over the Denver Nuggets on Friday night. "When you compete and you work hard, it shows up on the court,'' Thomas said. "From day one, he came into training camp in shape. The last two years, he wasn't. It's paying off for him.'' The Pacers lost to Denver 92-81 on Saturday on the final game of a five-game West Coast road trip. It was Indiana's only loss this season to a team with a losing record, and Thomas said the Pacers were tired and looking forward to going home. Back at Conseco Fieldhouse for the first time since Nov. 29, the Pacers appeared refreshed -- and a little testy -- while jumping out to a 28-point lead in the first half. They improved to an Eastern Conference-best 17-5 and gave Thomas his 100th career coaching victory. The Pacers were called for two technical fouls in the half, and the starting backcourt of Reggie Miller and Jamaal Tinsley combined for only two points. However, reserves Mercer and Croshere clicked in the second quarter, combining for 24 points mostly on long jumpers. Croshere reached double-digit scoring for only the second time this season. He made all three of his 3-point attempts in the first half and went 6-for-7 overall. "We have a great starting unit, but there are going to be nights when they're a little flat,'' Croshere said. "Those are the nights the second unit needs to step up.'' Croshere is slowly working his way back into the rotation after suffering a stress fracture in his right foot in September and missing the season's first 10 games. Last season, he rapidly fell out of Thomas' rotation and didn't play in half of the final eight games. Offseason trade rumors swirled, but the injury and a bloated salary prevented Indiana from finding the right deal. "It doesn't do me any good to get frustrated,'' Croshere said. "I'm just happy for the guys that play well, happy for the win, and I just really have confidence that I am going to have the opportunity.'' Croshere said the reserves have adjusted to ever-changing roles. Some games will mean lot of minutes and others will mean lots of sitting. "We've got guys on this team that can go out and score points like this all the time,'' Mercer said. "For us to win, everybody has to go out and play hard and be ready in any situation. Everybody just has to be patient.'' After Rodney White opened the second quarter with a 3-pointer, the Nuggets missed eight consecutive shots from the field and Indiana's lead widened to 53-25. Only Chris Whitney's 3 in the final seconds, which made it 53-28 at the half, prevented Denver from scoring the fewest points in a quarter and a half against Indiana. The Nuggets scored 13 points on 4-for-19 shooting in the second. Whitney led Denver with 14 points and White had 12. "It's too difficult to win when there is no scoring,'' Denver coach Jeff Bzdelik said. "The problem is, we can't put the ball in the hoop and when you struggle to score, this game is too tough.'' The Pacers maintained their cushion in the second half, mostly on the strength of their free-throw shooting. They went 32-for-42 from the line. The only cause for concern for Indiana is Miller's continuing offensive slide. He finished with four points and failed to score from the field (0-for-1) for the third time in the last six games, which included his first scoreless game since 1989. "It's a different mentality you have to play with,'' Thomas said. "It's really about the Pacers team and not about one individual.''

Game notes
Indiana's Jonathan Bender was limping in the locker room and said he pulled a calf muscle in his left leg. ...Indiana center Brad Miller missed the game with a sore left heel. He had started all 21 games. ... Indiana's Jeff Foster, whose streak of 115 consecutive games played ended Wednesday with a DNP-CD, grabbed 12 rebounds and scored four points in 31 minutes. ... Jermaine O'Neal, Tinsley and Juwan Howard were whistled for technical fouls in the first half. ... The Pacers held Toronto to 11 points in the third quarter and 27 points in the second half on Nov. 9.
